Yale historian David Blight served as advisor to the curators at the 9/11 Memorial and Museum. He and President Peter Salovey discuss commemorating the tremendous loss, the purpose of memorialization, and teaching complex history.

Hear the full Yale Talk podcast episode at http://president.yale.edu/yale-talk 

Link in Story 

#Yale

@yalelawschool #yale

Class Day speaker and double-EGOT composer Bobby Lopez ’97 created “The Beacon” specifically for the Harkness Tower carillon. 

Lopez is the songwriter behind “Frozen,” “Coco,” “Avenue Q,” and “Book of Mormon.”

The Beacon was played during today’s Class Day ceremony by graduate Paul Stelben ’21, the only carillonneur in Yale’s history to be certified by the Guild of Carillonneurs in North America, which he achieved as a sophomore.

Experience all the Class Day traditions and festivities, including more musical performances, at yale2021.yale.edu

node.text:
Yale Class Day begins now! Watch the full ceremony at: yale2021.yale.edu/class-day

Yale Glee Club came together in person for the first time in over a year to lend their voices to several favorite pieces from the group’s repertoire, including “Alleluia,” “Bright College Years,” and this piece — “Raise Your Voices Here” by @yalegleeclub Director Jeffrey Douma. 

The ceremony will include these performances, reflections from the graduating class, an address by songwriter Robert Lopez ’97, and many other traditions dating back to Class Day’s origins in the 19th century.

#yale #yalegleeclub #YaleAlumni #Yale2021

Don’t be fooled by Handsome Dan's resting smoosh face — he’s just as excited as you are about the reopening of Commons!

After nearly 4 years behind tarps and scaffolding, Yale Schwarzman Center opened last week. President Peter Salovey helped celebrate the occasion by serving lunch and greeting students, faculty, and staff. 

The opening of Commons for lunch, The Underground for seating, and The Bow Wow for grab-and-go service marks the first in a series of launches for the center’s various multi-use dining, performance, dance, and exhibition spaces in coming months.

In mid-September, @yale_schwarzman will begin offering small-group tours to help familiarize the Yale community with the building. These tours will include a peek inside The Dome, the refurbished performance space that once served as the Yale Banner yearbook office, and many of the reimagined spaces.

Commons retains its iconic 50-foot vaulted ceiling and restored timber-trusses, and environmental and theatrical systems were added. Excavations also created a new level of arts and dining spaces beneath Hewitt Quadrangle and Commons.

New collaborations include short- and long-term residencies of scholars, activists, business executives, and artists, now underway.

📷 2-5: Leigh Busby @busbyleigh

@handsomedanyale  #yale

One of Yale’s two newest residential colleges, Pauli Murray College is named for Anna Pauline “Pauli” Murray, a remarkable scholar, lawyer, and an early leader of the civil rights and women’s movements, who became the first African-American to receive a JSD (Doctor of Juridical Science) from @YaleLawSchool in 1965.

Murray was also a poet, writer, professor, and Episcopal priest, and Yale awarded her an honorary doctor from @YaleDivinitySchool in 1979. She led others with the idea that “the future of human society is on your side.”

Pauli Murray College’s official mascot is the lemur — since you can’t say ‘Pauli Murray’ without saying the word ‘lemur’ — and residents are “PauliMurs.”

#yale #YaleBlackAlumni #YaleWomen

“We had been hiking for almost four hours when the morning sun finally crested over the summit ridge of Mount Yale. I was at 12,800 feet on a clear and cool summer morning, hiking with 22 of my Yale classmates to the summit of the peak named in 1869 by Josiah Whitney, Yale Class of 1839, for his alma mater.

“My friends from the Pierson Class of 1992 had come from all parts of the country and as far as London to spend the last week of July together in Colorado, enjoying each other’s company, laughing at stories from long ago, cooking and sharing meals, discussing serious subjects, and attempting to climb a mountain that reaches 14,196 feet into the Colorado sky.”

Read the first-person account from Dave Belin ’92 of the ascent — and the longer journey that brought them all together.

Full story at: alumni.yale.edu/news

 📷: Rob Nevitt

@yalealumni #YaleAlumni #yale

Last week, incoming first-year students moved their belongings onto campus and quickly departed to attend Harvest, a pre-orientation program at family-owned farms across Connecticut.
